BLD-GA is a Common Lisp geometric algebra library.
By default it uses BLD-NUM for numeric arithmetic functions.
Use the package BLD-SYM to include generic functions for symbolic scalar coefficients.
The "w/sym" macro from BLD-SYM uses a single Maxima process in the background, processing symbolic arithmetic via a socket connection.
Otherwise, BLD-SYM calls Maxima multiple times (ie it's slow).

References
==========

"Efficient Implementation of Geometric Algebra"
http://staff.science.uva.nl/~fontijne/phd.html

...and the books:

"Geometric Algebra For Computer Science"
http://www.geometricalgebra.net/

"Geometric Algebra for Physicists"
http://www.mrao.cam.ac.uk/~cjld1/pages/book.htm

"New Foundations for Classical Mechanics"
http://geocalc.clas.asu.edu/html/NFCM.html

